///

///Description
@node "Description"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Status"
@toc "main"

   @{b}@{u}What is it:@{uu}@{ub}

   AmigaOSX  is  a  Bootscreen  for  Rainboot2  (or higher). With Rainboot
   you can Display a Picture, playing sound fx, music and Anims by booting
   your Amiga Computer.

@endnode
///
/// Requirements
@node "Requirements"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Description"
@toc "main"

   @{b}@{u}What Do You need.:@{uu}@{ub}

   · @{b}An Amiga or Amiga compat. Computer  System@{ub}, (with  a correct
     installation of OS3.x).
   · @{b}Rainboot2 (or higher) Bootsoftware@{ub}.
   · @{b}Good handling of Workbench and AmigaOS@{ub}



   You don't have Rainboot? Download it from Aminet, or visit the Homepage
   of Andreas Falkenhahn.

   @{b}Address@{ub}: http://www.home.pages.de/~Airsoft



   @{apen 2}@{bpen 3} Warning: @{apen 1}@{bpen 0}
   Do  not  use  a  unregistrate  Version  of   Rainboot.  You  can   have
   Disharmonies with the Bootconfig, please let you now register.

@endnode
///
/// Installation
@node "Installation"
@next "Edit"
@prev "Requirements"
@toc "main"

   @{b}@{u}Place for Data:@{uu}@{ub}

   @{b}1.@{ub} Open  the  Configs  Directory  of  extracted  AmigaOSX    Bootscreen
      Systems, and Open the Configs Directory of  your  Installt  Rainboot
      Systems.

   @{b}2.@{ub} Now copy via Drag & Drop a drawer e.g. aosXboot_640x480 to your
      Configs Directory of  Installt  Rainboot System. You  can rename the
      copied drawer e.g. "aosXboot".

   @{b}3.@{ub} Copy XHelvetica- and CGTimes-Directory, XHelvetica.font and
      CGTimes.font to "sys:fonts/"
      (The  XHelvetica  font  have  a  small modification to  the Original
      XHelvetica.font, character @{FG shine}@{b}¦@{ub}@{FG text} is one Pixel Up set`ed  -  that's all).

   @{b}4.@{ub} Installation Done.

   @{b}5.@{ub} @{" edit " link "Edit"} your startup-sequence

@endnode

@node "Edit"
@next "Course"
@prev "Installation"
@toc "main"

   @{b}@{u}Edit your startup-sequence:@{uu}@{ub}

   Edit your startup-sequence, run  the  Rainboot   command  direct  under
   "c:conclip" of your startup-sequence.

   @{b}c:rainboot@{ub} @{FG fill}>nil:@{FG text} @{FG shine}<path>AmigaOSX.config@{FG text} @{b}MODEID@{ub}=0x00039024 @{b}QUIET@{ub}

   You must give a correct ModeID, best, the same ID  of  your  Workbench,
   you can do this with the tool GetModeID, you can finde GetModeID in the
   tools Directory of Rainbbot. Run it  and Click in  the  Requester  your
   Screen  Resolution.  GetModeID  give you now your Hex ModeID. Please do
   not play with ModeID's. Use Only a ModeID for your Screen !



   @{u}MODEID's for some Standard AGA Resolutions:@{uu}

   @{b}DBLNTSC@{ub}:  HighRes flimmerfrei               640x400:  @{b}MODEID@{ub}=0x00099004
   @{b}NTSC@{ub}:     HighRes interlace                 640x400:  @{b}MODEID@{ub}=0x00019004

   @{b}Multiscan Productivity:@{ub}                     640x480:  @{b}MODEID@{ub}=0x00039024

   @{b}DBLPAL@{ub}:   HighRes flimmerfrei               640x512:  @{b}MODEID@{ub}=0x000A9004
   @{b}PAL@{ub}:      HighRes Interlace                 640x512:  @{b}MODEID@{ub}=0x00029004

   @{b}Super72@{ub}:  Super HighRes Interlace           800x600:  @{b}MODEID@{ub}=0x00089024



   @{apen 2}@{bpen 3} Note: @{apen 1}@{bpen 0}

   At the Moment i can't give any helps and support for Gfx-card  users. I
   don't  have  a  Gfx-card,  you  must self find out Your MODEID for Your
   Gfx-card Resolution. And don't  forget  "RTG"  Argument  behind  MODEID
   Argument.

@endnode
///
/// Course
@node "Course"
@next "Proplems"
@prev "Installation"
@toc "main"

   @{b}@{u}Course of Bootaccess:@{uu}@{ub}

   You have the Installation corrected  done'ed, now read the short course
   of Bootaccess.

   Boot your Amiga Computer, firstly You have a black Screen, seconds a go
   You see the aosX background he fade'ed to You.  In the  Background  You
   hear playing the Music, quietly. At the right You seeing the  Date  and
   Time  (only in 800x600 resolution config). Left from Time You  see  the
   AmigaBall, he is animated. All coming up's have a fx-ping.
   In the middle of your Bootscreen you see your OS Version  Number, (user
   with correct installt OS3.1 see OS3.1, user with correct installt OS3.9
   see OS3.9 (maybe - i hope) OS3.5 user see ...))
   Now begins the Processbar Moving with a fx-ping on the left of  Screen,
   the  Processbar  have short stops, this is right. Is the Process at the
   end, by Done, you have fx-ping too. Is the Bootprocess end'ed, now  the
   Screen is cleared of printed types with fx-pings. At the and You have a
   fade to white and in the next a fade to black, and the last fade  bring
   up Your Workbench. That's all ...

@endnode
